1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,820
 Thank you very much for this introduction. Greetings to all of you from Minnesota in the

2
00:00:10,820 --> 00:00:17,000
 United States. While I would have very much preferred to give this paper in person and be

3
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:22,720
 with you in the flesh, I'm grateful for the opportunity to share my paper remotely and of

4
00:00:22,720 --> 00:00:29,720
 of course I welcome your questions. In June 2025, can everybody hear me well?

5
00:00:29,720 --> 00:00:32,720
 Yeah, we can hear you well.

6
00:00:32,720 --> 00:00:39,720
 I think, yeah, I see some, I readily recognize some colleagues in the audience. Greetings to

7
00:00:39,720 --> 00:00:46,720
 all of you. In June 2025 the International Orthodox Theological Association that was just mentioned

8
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:52,720
 organized a conference in Rome in partnership with the Angelicum. As a part of this conference,

9
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:59,720
 we had the privilege of private audience with Pope Leo XIV. In his address to the conference

10
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:06,720
 participants, Pope Leo stated, and I quote, "The Council of Nicaea is not merely an event of

11
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:12,720
 the past, but a compass that must continue to guide us towards the full visible unity of

12
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:20,720
 all Christians." Elaborating on this point, the Pope added, "Together we believe in the triune

13
00:01:20,720 --> 00:01:26,720
 of God, in Christ as truly human and truly God, and in salvation through Jesus Christ according to the

14
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:31,720
 scriptures read in the church and under the guidance of the Holy Spirit, as well as in the church

15
00:01:31,720 --> 00:01:37,720
 baptism, the resurrection of the dead and eternal life." So what are the implications of acknowledging

16
00:01:37,720 --> 00:01:44,720
 this common faith for the prospect of intercommunion? I believe that these implications are quite serious.

17
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:51,720
 Hence, the question raised in the title of my paper is not rhetorical. Can the Nicene faith unite Catholic and

18
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:59,720
 Orthodox churches? The question is meant to be provocative. It would seem that an obvious answer is no. Our common

19
00:01:59,720 --> 00:02:06,720
 Nicene faith is not sufficient. This is because, first of all, there are both non-theological and theological

20
00:02:06,720 --> 00:02:13,720
 factors contributing to our lingering schism. The non-theological factors have to do with the church and

21
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:21,720
 state politics, sociology, psychology, present leadership, and so forth. I concur that these factors are very

22
00:02:21,720 --> 00:02:29,720
 serious, perhaps even decisive, but I would not be addressing them in this paper. So this paper focuses

23
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:35,720
 exclusively on the theological factors contributing to disunity. And I should also emphasize that my

24
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:42,720
 Nicene solution, if it has any merit at all, applies only to the prospect of Eucharistic communion

25
00:02:42,720 --> 00:02:49,720
 between Catholic and Orthodox churches. My solution does not, and I repeat, does not apply to the

26
00:02:49,720 --> 00:02:56,720
 reconciliation of the churches of the Reformation with either Catholics or the Orthodox. So my central thesis

27
00:02:56,720 --> 00:03:03,720
 is that the faith of Nicaea is sufficient, in fact, for the reestablishing of communion. I will put

28
00:03:03,720 --> 00:03:09,720
 forth two arguments in defense of this proposition, and then consider three objections, and reply to the

29
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:15,720
 objections. The Nicene faith expresses our common belief in the triune God, the full divinity of Christ,

30
00:03:15,720 --> 00:03:21,720
 and the divine incarnation. The expanded version of the Nicene Creed that was endorsed by the Council of

31
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:27,720
 Constantinople also adds a statement about the four marks of the church, baptism, resurrection, and the

32
00:03:27,720 --> 00:03:33,720
 life of the world to come. Catholic and Orthodox Christians are aware that we share these fundamentals

33
00:03:33,720 --> 00:03:39,720
 of our faith, yet we are also painfully aware of numerous obstacles to unity. The crucial methodological

34
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:45,720
 question or conundrum to address before getting to the specific theological issues is this: which

35
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:50,720
 theological differences should be considered church dividing, and which differences should not be seen

36
00:03:50,720 --> 00:03:57,720
 as such? Clearly, not all doctrines are of equal value. But how should one mark the relevant

37
00:03:57,720 --> 00:04:03,720
 distinction? Some direction in resolving this methodological question is offered in the document of

38
00:04:03,720 --> 00:04:11,720
 of Vatican II and Ecumenism, Unitatis Red Integratio. And let me quote from the 11th paragraph of that document:

39
00:04:11,720 --> 00:04:17,720
 "Moreover, in ecumenical dialogue, Catholic theologians standing fast by the teaching of the Church and

40
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:23,720
 investigating the divine mysteries with the separated brethren must proceed with love for the truth, with

41
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:29,720
 charity, and with humility. When comparing doctrines with one another, they should remember that in Catholic

42
00:04:29,720 --> 00:04:35,720
 doctrine there exists a hierarchy of truths, since they vary in their relation to the fundamental Christian faith.

43
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:41,720
 Thus the way will be opened by which, through fraternal rivalry, all will be stirred to a deeper

44
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:47,720
 understanding and a clearer presentation of the unfathomable riches of Christ." So the concept of the hierarchy

45
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:53,720
 of truths was introduced into conciliate discussions of the document on ecumenism by Archbishop Andrea Pangrazio

46
00:04:53,720 --> 00:05:07,720
 in his speech on November 25, 1963. And so to unpack this concept, which is not developed in Unitatis Red Integratio,

47
00:05:07,720 --> 00:05:13,720
 I'm going to quote Pangrazio extensively. So here's what Archbishop said:

48
00:05:13,720 --> 00:05:21,720
 "In the first place, it seems to me very important to discover exactly what unity already exists between Christians

49
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:27,720
 and how much diversity can still be found alongside it. We must pay great attention to the hierarchical order

50
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:31,720
 which exists between the revealed truths by which the mystery of Christ is expressed

51
00:05:31,720 --> 00:05:35,720
 and the ecclesiastical elements making up the Church.

52
00:05:35,720 --> 00:05:39,720
 And even if all the revealed truths were believed with one equally divine faith,

53
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:43,720
 and all the constitutive elements of the Church were held with the same fidelity,

54
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:51,720
 they would not all have the right to occupy the same place." And so here he then introduces a crucial distinction.

55
00:05:51,720 --> 00:05:57,720
 There are truths, says Pangrazio, related to the final order, for example,

56
00:05:57,720 --> 00:06:03,720
 the mystery of the Trinity, incarnation, redemption, love and grace of God towards sinful man, eternal life, and the kingdom.

57
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:11,720
 Other truths related to the order are related to the order of means of salvation.

58
00:06:11,720 --> 00:06:13,720
 So the distinction is between the final order and the means of salvation.

59
00:06:13,720 --> 00:06:21,720
 As for example, the seven sacraments, the hierarchical structure of the Church, the apostolic succession, and so on.

60
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:29,720
 These are means which have been given by Christ to the Church for its pilgrimage on earth and will disappear when that pilgrimage is ended.

61
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:37,720
 Now the doctrinal differences between Christians are concerned less, says he, with the primordial truths, the final order,

62
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:43,720
 than with these last related to the order of means, and without any doubt subordinate to the former.

63
00:06:43,720 --> 00:06:49,720
 One can say that the unity of Christians consists in faith and commitment related to the final order.

64
00:06:49,720 --> 00:06:57,720
 If we give explicit expression to this ordering of truths and elements, I think we would have a better perspective on the unity already existing between all Christians,

65
00:06:57,720 --> 00:07:04,720
 who form a family already united by the primordial truths of the Christian religion." End of quotation.

66
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:14,720
 So thus understood, the concept of the hierarchy of truths is helpful for differentiating the doctrines that are Church dividing and those that are not.

67
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:23,720
 And so my simple point here is that those belonging to the final order, if we differ on those, in fact, we should adjudicate the differences.

68
00:07:23,720 --> 00:07:31,720
 And those belonging to the means of salvation, we should be significantly less worried about those, because at least I treat them as non-Church dividing.

69
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:40,720
 And of course there is, again, there is really no, presently there is no agreement on what counts, what set of doctrines should count in fact as Church dividing.

70
00:07:40,720 --> 00:07:47,720
 So before discussing any controversial, practical or doctrinal issue, we should ask first whether the issue is a deal-breaker.

71
00:07:47,720 --> 00:07:56,720
 If we fail to address this question, we'll continue spending much time wandering in the wilderness of disputed questions and, in the process, losing our sense of direction.

72
00:07:56,720 --> 00:08:05,720
 To enter the promised land, where Communicatio and Sacris becomes a reality, one needs to know what it would take to get there.

73
00:08:05,720 --> 00:08:11,720
 Let me now press the central question of this paper yet again: Can the Nicene faith reunite our Churches?

74
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:21,720
 I maintain that the common acceptance and profession of the Nicene faith could serve as a sufficient condition of the Eucharistic Communion for the following two major reasons.

75
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:25,720
 My reasons have to do with the logic of the Sacrament of Baptism and the Eucharist.

76
00:08:25,720 --> 00:08:32,720
 For both Churches, the faith professed in Baptism is the faith expressed in the Nicene Constantinopolitan Creed.

77
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:46,720
 The ancient custom of Traditio and Reditio Symboli, the handing over of the Creed to the adult catechumens and their recitation of the Creed back to the Church ministers before baptism confirms this judgment.

78
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:54,720
 In the early Church, the doctrinal core of the adult catechumenate was defined by the exposition of the Creed, which took place during Lent.

79
00:08:54,720 --> 00:09:01,720
 The extant expositions of the Creed include the catechetical sermons of Cyril of Jerusalem and Theodoro Mopsiastia.

80
00:09:01,720 --> 00:09:05,720
 Those of us patristically trained would readily recognize those sources.

81
00:09:05,720 --> 00:09:13,720
 When the adult catechumenate is done properly in our Churches today, the Trinitarian and Incarnational vision of the Creed constitutes its core.

82
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:21,720
 Replacing this doctrinal core with other teachings, no matter how relevant, will result in a distorted picture of the fundamental Christian faith.

83
00:09:21,720 --> 00:09:31,720
 Let us also recall that the main condition for the validity of baptism, for the Orthodox and Catholics alike, is that it is performed in the name of the Trinity, the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.

84
00:09:31,720 --> 00:09:36,720
 The presence of water and the intention of the minister are present in both communions.

85
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:43,720
 As for the liturgy, the same Nicene faith is a doctrinal deposit that believers recite before communion.

86
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:58,720
 According to the document, the mystery of the Church and of the Eucharist in the light of the mystery of the Holy Trinity, produced by the Joint Orthodox Catholic Theological Commission and adopted at the Munich meeting of 1982, and I quote:

87
00:09:58,720 --> 00:10:02,720
 Correct faith, or orthodoxy, is inherent in the Eucharistic koinonia.

88
00:10:02,720 --> 00:10:13,720
 This orthodoxy is expressed most clearly through the proclamation of the symbol of faith, which is a summary of the apostolic tradition, of which the bishop is the witness in virtue of his succession.

89
00:10:13,720 --> 00:10:23,720
 The apostolic tradition was preserved in the Church with the help of the ancient rules of faith, cited and discussed by Justin Mata, Irenaeus of Lyon, Tertullian, and other Church Fathers.

90
00:10:23,720 --> 00:10:30,720
 The rules of faith, or regular fidei, were the predecessors of the concilia creeds, such as the Nicene Creed.

91
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:39,720
 The rules of faith informed and shaped the life of the Church before the Council of Nicaea, including the developing canon of the New Testament, prayers, and liturgical practice.

92
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:51,720
 As one of the major differences in the Nicene faith that has historically provided a pretext for hardening the division between the Latin West and the Byzantine East, namely the Filioquia Clause,

93
00:10:51,720 --> 00:11:00,720
 The conclusion of the study on the Filioquia put forth by the North American Orthodox Catholic Consultation in 2003 seems sound and prudent.

94
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:01,720
 And I quote:

95
00:11:01,720 --> 00:11:17,720
 We offer these recommendations to our churches in the conviction, based on our own intense study and discussion, that our traditions differ, that our traditions different ways of understanding the procession of the Holy Spirit need no longer divide us.

96
00:11:17,720 --> 00:11:32,720
 We believe, rather, that our profession of the ancient Creed of Constantinople must be allowed to become, by our uniform practice and our new attempt at mutual understanding, the basis for a more conscious unity in the one faith that all theology simply seeks to clarify and to deepen.

97
00:11:32,720 --> 00:11:49,720
 So, the conclusion here is that the use or non-use of the Filioquia Clause in the Creed should not become Church dividing, and then the general recommendation is that in the ecumenical context that clause is dropped.

98
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:52,720
 So, that was the basic idea.

99
00:11:52,720 --> 00:11:57,720
 It's important that we start to see the forest behind the trees of our differences.

100
00:11:57,720 --> 00:12:06,720
 Once we realize that we live in the same forest, we should let this realization sink in and influence our approach to theological education and pastoral care.

101
00:12:06,720 --> 00:12:16,720
 Now, if and when we agree that the profession of the Nicene faith is sufficient for full communion, we could proceed to work towards its full restoration with a greater sense of direction and purpose.

102
00:12:16,720 --> 00:12:23,720
 Now, there will be many bumps on the road to unity, and the main obstacles are practical and political rather than theological.

103
00:12:23,720 --> 00:12:32,720
 And I noted that non-theological issues behind the issues are perhaps really quite significant, but I personally am undeterred.

104
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:43,720
 And once full communion is restored, the Church leaders and scholars of the East and West could then identify and continue to discuss a potentially inexhaustible list of questiones disputate.

105
00:12:43,720 --> 00:12:46,720
 You know, that's what we're paid to do, and that's normal.

106
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:47,720
 And we'll love it.

107
00:12:47,720 --> 00:12:49,720
 And I think it's a good thing.

108
00:12:49,720 --> 00:12:51,720
 I don't think it's an exercise in futility.

109
00:12:51,720 --> 00:12:55,720
 Ecclesiological questions such as primacy, synodality, and apostolic succession.

110
00:12:55,720 --> 00:13:02,720
 Mariology and its soteriological implications, sacramental theology and its practical implications.

111
00:13:02,720 --> 00:13:07,720
 Even eschatology will need to continue to be elucidated and discussed.

112
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:14,720
 Some elements will continue to be contested, but other elements that are more characteristic of one tradition could be adopted by the other tradition.

113
00:13:14,720 --> 00:13:24,720
 In fact, the West has now been listening to the East for nearly a century, as far as theology of icon, spirituality, soteriology, and even synodality are concerned.

114
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:28,720
 This type of receptive ecumenism has already borne plentiful fruits.

115
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:42,720
 However, we should engage in receptive ecumenism with the filial assurance that our continuing differences regarding the matters pertaining to the means of salvation are not church dividing.

116
00:13:42,720 --> 00:13:46,720
 And remember, Pangratio's distinction between the final order and the means.

117
00:13:46,720 --> 00:13:55,720
 The ecumenical reception of each other's traditions should fittingly occur and would become easier to facilitate after our churches have been united in the Eucharist.

118
00:13:55,720 --> 00:14:08,720
 So why should the controversial issues pertaining to the means of salvation prevent the restoration of the Eucharistic communion if neither our rites of initiation nor our liturgies require their adjudication?

119
00:14:08,720 --> 00:14:12,720
 And so now I come to considering potential objections.

120
00:14:12,720 --> 00:14:18,720
 I will now consider three objections to my proposal and briefly respond to each of them.

121
00:14:18,720 --> 00:14:25,720
 First, it seems that the proposal reduces the doctrinal foundation of unity to the lowest common denominator.

122
00:14:25,720 --> 00:14:31,720
 This would have the effect of minimizing the significance of the doctrines that are not explicitly professed in the Nicene Creed.

123
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:48,720
 For example, since the dogmas about Mary in the corollaries of the doctrine of the incarnation are the corollaries of the doctrine of the incarnation, they should be included in the list of disputed questions to be settled before the restoration of full communion.

124
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:59,720
 Now, the Roman Catholic Church considers its dogmas about of Mary's immaculate conception and bodily assumption to be binding with ignoring our doctrinal differences regarding these doctrines create greater problems down the road.

125
00:14:59,720 --> 00:15:06,720
 Would the privileging of the Nicene faith have the effect of relativizing all doctrines not explicitly professed in the creed?

126
00:15:06,720 --> 00:15:07,720
 No, it's a serious worry.

127
00:15:07,720 --> 00:15:14,720
 Now, I agree that the Nicene faith cannot be treated in isolation from other doctrines, including those about Mary.

128
00:15:14,720 --> 00:15:22,720
 The Christological and satiriological implications of the Immaculate Conception require a detailed ecumenical discussion.

129
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:25,720
 I fully expect important controversial points to remain.

130
00:15:25,720 --> 00:15:35,720
 So I don't, I'm not particularly optimistic about the prospect of actually agreement on Mariology fully.

131
00:15:35,720 --> 00:15:41,720
 However, I do not consider the professional rejection of this doctrine to be an impediment to sharing communion.

132
00:15:41,720 --> 00:15:47,720
 To be clear, I don't suggest that the differences are trivial or should be sweat under the rug.

133
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:52,720
 On the contrary, those differences must be faced squarely within the framework of receptive ecumenism.

134
00:15:52,720 --> 00:16:01,720
 By receptive ecumenism, I mean an approach to ecumenical dialogue that focuses on what can be learned with integrity from the Christian traditions other than one's own.

135
00:16:01,720 --> 00:16:08,720
 To be clear, the goal is not the abandonment of one's own cherished beliefs, but growth and communion with others.

136
00:16:08,720 --> 00:16:15,720
 My proposal makes the logical and receptive forms of ecumenism complementary and mutually supporting.

137
00:16:15,720 --> 00:16:36,720
 Now, to turn to the second objection, it seems that the proposal attempts to bypass the authoritative decisions made by the later councils by appealing to a fixed point in the church's past, to an imagined golden age, when the debate over the Council of Nicaea status was settled and its decisions, including its creed, became authoritative.

138
00:16:36,720 --> 00:16:41,720
 You know, sometime, I don't know, at the end of the fourth and the beginning of the fifth century.

139
00:16:41,720 --> 00:16:53,720
 The sufficiency of Nicaea would have the effect of undermining the authority of the other six ecumenical councils for the Chalcedonian Orthodox tradition and the other 20 councils for the Catholic tradition.

140
00:16:53,720 --> 00:16:58,720
 Now, what reasons do we have for stopping at Nicaea and not, say, at Chalcedon or later council?

141
00:16:58,720 --> 00:17:13,720
 Now, in response, I need to clarify that in my proposal, the faith of Nicaea does not function as a fixed point in time, but as a living confession of faith that is more relevant today than it was in the fourth century.

142
00:17:13,720 --> 00:17:23,720
 The main reason for this is that in the fourth century, the creed was not recited at every liturgy, but functioned in the context of the pre-baptismal catechumenate primarily.

143
00:17:23,720 --> 00:17:32,720
 Nevertheless, for about 1500 years, Orthodox and Catholic Christians have been using the Nicene faith as their central and common confession in the liturgy.

144
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:40,720
 Furthermore, the Nicene faith is the common foundation of all Christian traditions that accept the authority of at least one ecumenical council.

145
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:46,720
 The worries regarding the status of the other councils could be handled under the auspices of receptive ecumenism.

146
00:17:46,720 --> 00:17:58,720
 For the six councils that followed after Nicaea, and that are recognized by the Chalcedonian Orthodox and Catholics as ecumenical, there is little for these two churches to receive a debate, except perhaps the filioque.

147
00:17:58,720 --> 00:18:11,720
 Again, so the point is, the commitment to Nicaea doesn't relativize the following six councils because, again, Catholics and Chalcedonian Orthodox already take those councils as authority.

148
00:18:11,720 --> 00:18:24,720
 Nevertheless, the question of how the remaining syncs ecumenical councils are introduced and discussed has implications for the dialogues with the Assyrian Church of the East and especially with the Oriental Church.

149
00:18:24,720 --> 00:18:33,720
 So I'm really concerned about the Oriental component here very much: the Copts, the Egyptians, sorry, the Armenians, Ethiopians, etc.

150
00:18:33,720 --> 00:18:43,720
 The appeal to the Nicene faith has the advantage of potentially bringing the Oriental churches on board too, or at least not alienating their leaders.

151
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:53,720
 So the third and final objection is that my proposal is question-begging because it fails to address the elephant in the room, namely papal authority.

152
00:18:53,720 --> 00:19:02,720
 The practical and political aspects of papal primacy affect Church governance and Church unity to such an extent that this issue is unavoidable.

153
00:19:02,720 --> 00:19:12,720
 We do not need a rerun of the Council of Ferrara Florence, where an attempt was made to compel the Greek Orthodox side to accept the authority of the Pope by political pressure.

154
00:19:12,720 --> 00:19:21,720
 If we attempt unity before resolving the issue of universal primacy, we will simply invite additional tensions and potential internal schisms.

155
00:19:21,720 --> 00:19:29,720
 Now, in response, I wish to acknowledge that papal authority, primacy, and synodality are indeed questions of uttermost importance.

156
00:19:29,720 --> 00:19:33,720
 We cannot hide our theological heads in the sand from these issues.

157
00:19:33,720 --> 00:19:41,720
 Thankfully, in the 21st century, these issues have been the focus of formal dialogues in Ravenna, Chieti, and Alexandria.

158
00:19:41,720 --> 00:19:52,720
 In addition, the Orthodox theologians have published collective studies on primacy, whereas the Catholic theologians got to work on such issues as autocephaly and synodality.

159
00:19:52,720 --> 00:19:58,720
 The synods and synodality that were encouraged and summoned by Pope Francis are an important step in the right direction.

160
00:19:58,720 --> 00:20:12,720
 The Bishop of Rome document of 2024, and the primacy that was put forth by the Dicastry for the Promotion of Christian Unity, also made considerable progress towards a mutually acceptable understanding and practice of universal primacy.

161
00:20:12,720 --> 00:20:21,720
 We should continue moving towards the resolution of these issues with filial assurance that they could be handled under the auspices of receptive ecumenism.

162
00:20:21,720 --> 00:20:32,720
 If both churches acknowledge that these issues are not church dividing, we could trust the Holy Spirit to help us resolve them within the unified church.

163
00:20:32,720 --> 00:20:44,720
 Since the above stated objections cannot be quietly set aside, an amendment of my original proposal that the Nicene faith is sufficient for the restoration of full communion is in order.

164
00:20:44,720 --> 00:20:49,720
 I suggest that the proposal is best expressed in terms of a formula of reunion.

165
00:20:49,720 --> 00:21:03,720
 My proposal is inspired by a historical formula put forth by Cyril of Alexandria and John of Antioch in 433, as they were faced with new theological challenges when interpreting the second article of the Creed.

166
00:21:03,720 --> 00:21:10,720
 That formula of reunion was useful in bringing the churches that were estranged after the Council of Ephesus back together.

167
00:21:10,720 --> 00:21:21,720
 The formula played this reconciling role without either being a new creedal statement or a digmatic definition of an ecumenical council, and I think that was its genius.

168
00:21:21,720 --> 00:21:30,720
 The formula proved effective because it played an auxiliary hermeneutical role without mandating a new article of faith or without modifying the creed.

169
00:21:30,720 --> 00:21:43,720
 Chalcedon actually pushed things in some interesting ways, although it wasn't entirely clear, of course, at Chalcedon, as to what Chalcedon was in fact doing when it profited its definition.

170
00:21:43,720 --> 00:21:47,720
 The formula of reunion of 433 did not intend anything of the sort.

171
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:56,720
 So what I offer below should be taken as a working text and a recommendation to be further discussed and revised in the bilateral dialogues.

172
00:21:56,720 --> 00:22:02,720
 So here is my Nicene formula of reunion between the Roman Catholic and the Orthodox churches.

173
00:22:02,720 --> 00:22:09,720
 So I quote: "By the grace of God, the Nicene faith has been given to our churches as their common doctrinal foundation."

174
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:17,720
 We agree that the profession of this faith is sufficient for the restoration of the Eucharistic communion between our churches.

175
00:22:17,720 --> 00:22:25,720
 We acknowledge that the remaining doctrinal and practical differences, while numerous and considerable, are not church dividing.

176
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:37,720
 Such differences include an account of the origin and the procession of the Holy Spirit, or the Filioquia, the church order, especially the exercise of the universal primacy synodality and the practice of autocephaly,

177
00:22:37,720 --> 00:22:45,720
 Mariology, sacramental theology, theological anthropology, church calendar, and the veneration of different saints.

178
00:22:45,720 --> 00:22:52,720
 We commit to the exploration of these differences in the spirit of humility, seeking mutual understanding and enrichment.

179
00:22:52,720 --> 00:22:59,720
 With the help of the Holy Spirit, we pledge to seek truth together in order to overcome any remaining obstacles that keep us apart.

180
00:22:59,720 --> 00:23:10,720
 We appeal to the leaders of our churches around the world to participate in the process of bringing our churches together through prayer, instruction, and acts of service."

181
00:23:10,720 --> 00:23:14,720
 So that's my version of the formula of reunion.

182
00:23:14,720 --> 00:23:17,720
 And I thank you very much for your attention.

183
00:23:17,720 --> 00:23:18,720
 Thank you very much for your attention.

